+# SharedMemory
+
+> Allocate ArrayBuffer and typed-array payloads backed by shared memory.
+
+Process: [Main](../glossary.md#main-process), [Renderer](../glossary.md#renderer-process)
+
+`SharedMemory` lets the main process create a shared memory pool for a renderer
+frame. Buffers allocated inside `SharedMemory.withAllocator` are backed by
+that pool and are restored automatically when passed through Electron IPC.
+
+For repeated binary messages, `SharedMemory` can also create a
+`SharedMemoryChannel`. A channel sends shared-backed payload references using
+IPC only as a readable notification. When `copyFallback` is `allow`, or when
+ring slot options are supplied explicitly, the channel also allocates reusable
+shared-memory ring slots for ordinary `ArrayBuffer` and `ArrayBufferView`
+inputs.
+
+Channel messages carry an optional unsigned 32-bit numeric `tag`. The receiver
+always gets the raw payload as an `ArrayBuffer`; use the tag to decide whether
+to read it as `Uint8Array`, `Float32Array`, `DataView`, or another typed view.
+
+## Methods
+
+The `SharedMemory` module has the following methods:
+
+**Note:** Experimental APIs are marked as such and could be removed in the future.
+
+### `SharedMemory.createPool(options)` _Experimental_
+
+* `options` [CreateSharedMemoryPoolOptions](structures/create-shared-memory-pool-options.md)
+
+Creates a shared memory pool and registers it in the main process and target
+renderer frame.
+
+If `options.size` is omitted, Electron creates a 64 MiB pool.
+
+> [!NOTE]
+> This method is only available in the main process.
+
+Returns `Promise<SharedMemoryPool>` - Resolves with the shared memory pool.
+
+### `SharedMemory.getPoolStats(pool)` _Experimental_
+
+* `pool` [SharedMemoryPool](structures/shared-memory-pool.md)
+
+Returns [`SharedMemoryPoolStats | null`](structures/shared-memory-pool-stats.md) -
+Current allocation counters for `pool`, or `null` if the pool is not registered
+in the current process.
+
+The counters describe allocations made by the current process. If a renderer is
+the producer, call this method in that renderer to inspect renderer-side pool
+usage.
+
+### `SharedMemory.createChannel(pool, options)` _Experimental_
+
+* `pool` [SharedMemoryPool](structures/shared-memory-pool.md)
+* `options` [SharedMemoryChannelOptions](structures/shared-memory-channel-options.md)
+
+Creates a sending `SharedMemoryChannel` endpoint backed by `pool`.
+
+The current implementation is intended for renderer-to-main streaming. Create
+the sending endpoint in the renderer and create a matching receiving endpoint in
+the main process with `SharedMemory.acceptChannel`.
+
+When `copyFallback` is omitted or set to `throw`, and no ring slot options are
+provided, this method does not allocate copy-fallback ring storage. This is the
+recommended mode for shared-backed payloads created with
+`SharedMemory.withAllocator`.
+
+Returns `SharedMemoryChannel` - The sending channel endpoint.
+
+### `SharedMemory.acceptChannel(pool, options)` _Experimental_
+
+* `pool` [SharedMemoryPool](structures/shared-memory-pool.md)
+* `options` Object
+  * `name` string - Logical channel name.
+  * `overflow` string (optional) - Ring-full behavior. Can be `drop-oldest`,
+    `drop-newest`, or `throw`. Default is `drop-oldest`.
+  * `oversized` string (optional) - Oversized-payload behavior. Can be
+    `allocate`, `drop`, or `throw`. Default is `allocate`.
+  * `oversizedSlotCount` number (optional) - Slot count for dynamically
+    allocated oversized rings. Default is `2`.
+  * `views` Record\<number, Function\> (optional) - Numeric tag to typed-array or
+    `DataView` constructor map used by `message.view()`.
+  * `maxTagSize` number (optional) - Maximum encoded tag metadata length for
+    copy-fallback rings. Default is `1024`.
+
+Creates a receiving `SharedMemoryChannel` endpoint in the main process. The
+endpoint accepts ring descriptors announced by a renderer endpoint with the same
+pool id and channel name.
+
+Returns `SharedMemoryChannel` - The opened channel endpoint.
+
+> [!NOTE]
+> This method is only available in the main process.
+
+### `SharedMemory.openChannel(pool, descriptor[, options])` _Experimental_
+
+* `pool` [SharedMemoryPool](structures/shared-memory-pool.md)
+* `descriptor` [SharedMemoryChannelDescriptor](structures/shared-memory-channel-descriptor.md)
+* `options` Object (optional)
+  * `overflow` string (optional) - Ring-full behavior. Can be `drop-oldest`,
+    `drop-newest`, or `throw`. Default is `drop-oldest`.
+  * `oversized` string (optional) - Oversized-payload behavior. Can be
+    `allocate`, `drop`, or `throw`. Default is `allocate`.
+  * `oversizedSlotCount` number (optional) - Slot count for dynamically
+    allocated oversized rings. Default is `2`.
+  * `views` Record\<number, Function\> (optional) - Numeric tag to typed-array or
+    `DataView` constructor map used by `message.view()`.
+  * `maxTagSize` number (optional) - Maximum encoded tag metadata length for
+    copy-fallback rings. Default is `1024`.
+
+Opens an existing channel descriptor in the current process.
+
+Returns `SharedMemoryChannel` - The opened channel endpoint.
+
+### `SharedMemory.withAllocator(pool, callback[, options])` _Experimental_
+
+* `pool` [SharedMemoryPool](structures/shared-memory-pool.md)
+* `callback` Function
+* `options` [SharedAllocatorOptions](structures/shared-allocator-options.md) (optional)
+
+Runs `callback` while length-based `ArrayBuffer` and typed-array allocations are
+redirected to `pool`. By default, `new ArrayBuffer(size)` and
+`new Uint8Array(length)` style constructors are shared-backed. Array-like
+constructor inputs are not shared-backed unless `options.arrayLike` is `true`.
+
+When `options.channel` is provided, allocated shared-backed buffers and views are
+affined to that channel. Electron pre-registers their payload id during
+allocation and stores channel-private fast-path metadata on the exact allocated
+object. Later `channel.send(data[, tag])` calls for that object can skip
+descriptor discovery and descriptor registration at send time. The channel must
+use the same pool.
+
+Channel-affined allocations reserve reusable bucket-sized backing blocks
+internally, while the JavaScript `ArrayBuffer` or typed array keeps the requested
+logical byte length. This allows variable-size payloads, such as encoded binary
+chunks, to reuse the same shared block after release instead of consuming new
+pool space for every distinct byte length.
+
+Only shared-backed values that are returned from the allocator callback, or are
+reachable from the returned object, remain valid after the callback returns.
+Temporary channel-affined allocations made inside the callback are detached and
+returned to the channel's reusable allocator automatically. Return every
+shared-backed value that must outlive the callback.
+
+When a channel-affined payload is sent with `channel.send(data[, tag])`, the
+default `ownership: 'transfer'` mode transfers the payload to the channel. The
+sender-side `ArrayBuffer` is detached when possible and must not be used again.
+After the receiver's message handler returns, or after a retained message lease
+is released, Electron returns the shared block to the sending channel's reusable
+allocator.
+
+With `ownership: 'borrow'`, `send()` does not detach the sender-side
+`ArrayBuffer` immediately. The sender-side object remains shared-backed until
+the receiver releases the message, then Electron detaches it and returns the
+shared block to the reusable allocator. Use this when the receiver may call
+`message.retain()` and the producer will not mutate the borrowed bytes while the
+receiver owns them.
+
+With `delivery: 'latest'`, the sender keeps ownership of channel-affined
+payloads and may send the same shared-backed payload again while earlier
+messages are still in-flight. The receiver may observe the latest bytes in that
+slot instead of the bytes as they were when `send()` was called. This mode is
+intended for latest-value streams.
+
+If the channel was created with `allocator: true`, `allocator: 'auto'`, or an
+allocator options object, `SharedMemory.withAllocator(pool, callback,
+{ channel })` first tries to satisfy length-based allocations from preallocated
+channel slots. In `delivery: 'latest'` mode, `channel.send(data[, tag])` makes a
+sent allocator slot reusable for later allocator scopes. This keeps the
+`withAllocator` API shape while moving most shared-backed wrapper setup to
+channel creation time.
+
+This is the recommended allocation mode for high-rate channel producers:
+
+```js
+const data = SharedMemory.withAllocator(pool, () => {
+  const out = new Uint8Array(size);
+  // Fill out before sending.
+  return out;
+}, { channel });
+
+channel.send(data, tag);
+```
+
+Returns `T` - The value returned by `callback`.
+
+### `SharedMemory.isSharedBacked(value)` _Experimental_
+
+* `value` any
+
+Returns `boolean` - Whether `value` is an `ArrayBuffer`, `Buffer`, typed array,
+or `DataView` backed by an Electron shared memory pool.
+
+### `SharedMemory.describe(value)` _Experimental_
+
+* `value` any
+
+Returns [`SharedMemoryDescriptor | null`](structures/shared-memory-descriptor.md) -
+A descriptor for a shared-backed `ArrayBuffer`, `Buffer`, typed array, or
+`DataView`, or `null` when `value` is not shared-backed.
+
+This is an advanced API. Normal Electron IPC wraps shared-backed payloads
+automatically.
+
+### `SharedMemory.view(descriptor)` _Experimental_
+
+* `descriptor` [SharedMemoryDescriptor](structures/shared-memory-descriptor.md)
+
+Returns `any` - A local `ArrayBuffer`, `Buffer`, typed array, or `DataView` view
+for `descriptor`, or `null` if the descriptor cannot be mapped in the current
+process.
+
+This is an advanced API. Normal Electron IPC unwraps shared-backed payloads
+automatically.
+
+### `SharedMemory.release(value)` _Experimental_
+
+* `value` any
+
+Returns `boolean` - Whether local shared-memory tracking was released for
+`value`.
+
+The mapped shared memory backing store remains owned by V8 and is unmapped when
+the corresponding `ArrayBuffer` backing store is garbage collected.
+
+## Class: SharedMemoryChannel
+
+> A reusable shared-memory channel for repeated binary messages.
+
+`SharedMemoryChannel` receives messages through a single handler registered with
+`setMessageHandler()`.
+
+### Instance Properties
+
+#### `channel.name` _Readonly_
+
+A `string` property containing the logical channel name.
+
+#### `channel.pool` _Readonly_
+
+A `SharedMemoryPool` property containing the pool used by this local endpoint.
+
+#### `channel.descriptor` _Readonly_
+
+A `SharedMemoryChannelDescriptor` property containing the serializable ring
+layout for this endpoint.
+
+#### `channel.overflow` _Readonly_
+
+A `string` property containing the ring-full policy used by `send`.
+
+#### `channel.oversized` _Readonly_
+
+A `string` property containing the oversized-payload policy used by `send`.
+
+#### `channel.oversizedSlotCount` _Readonly_
+
+A `number` property containing the slot count used when `send` allocates an
+oversized ring.
+
+#### `channel.maxTagSize` _Readonly_
+
+A `number` property containing the maximum encoded tag metadata length used by
+copy-fallback rings.
+
+#### `channel.ownership` _Readonly_
+
+A `string` property containing the shared-backed payload ownership policy used
+by `send`. It is either `transfer` or `borrow`.
+
+#### `channel.delivery` _Readonly_
+
+A `string` property containing the shared-backed payload delivery policy used by
+`send`. It is either `snapshot` or `latest`.
+
+### Instance Methods
+
+#### `channel.getAllocatorStats()` _Experimental_
+
+Returns `Object` - Diagnostic counters for the channel's preallocated allocator.
+The result includes `enabled`, `overflow`, `classFallback`, and per-class
+`size`, `count`, `free`, `hits`, `misses`, `largerFallbacks`, and
+`dynamicFallbacks` values.
+
+#### `channel.send(data[, tag])` _Experimental_
+
+* `data` ArrayBuffer | ArrayBufferView - Binary payload to queue.
+* `tag` number | null (optional) - Unsigned 32-bit integer tag used to route or
+  interpret the binary payload.
+
+When `data` is backed by the same `SharedMemoryPool` as the channel, transfers a
+reference to the existing shared-backed bytes without copying the payload.
+Non-shared-backed inputs throw by default. Set `copyFallback` to `allow` in the
+channel options to copy ordinary `ArrayBuffer` and `ArrayBufferView` inputs into
+a reusable shared-memory ring slot.
+
+`tag` is intended for lightweight routing or interpretation of the binary
+payload, for example a message type. Numeric tags avoid string serialization on
+the fast notification path.
+
+When shared-backed payloads have already been affined to the channel, repeated
+`send()` calls are internally coalesced. Applications continue to call
+`channel.send(data[, tag])`; Electron batches the native wakeup for bursty
+fire-and-forget sends without adding a public batching API.
+
+Returns `boolean` - Whether the message was queued.
+
+> [!NOTE]
+> This method does not recursively scan objects for shared-backed buffers. Pass
+> the binary payload as the first argument and pass small control information as
+> `tag`.
+
+> [!IMPORTANT]
+> `send()` transfers ownership of shared-backed payloads to the channel. After
+> `send()` succeeds, the sender-side `ArrayBuffer` is detached when possible and
+> must not be read or written again. If the receiver needs to keep the payload
+> after the handler returns, it must call `message.retain()` and later release
+> the returned lease.
+>
+> If the channel was created with `ownership: 'borrow'`, the sender-side
+> `ArrayBuffer` is detached only after the receiver releases the message.
+> Receiver-side `retain()` delays that detach and the reusable allocator release.
+> It does not freeze the bytes against writes made by the sender before release.
+>
+> If the channel was created with `delivery: 'latest'`, `send()` keeps the
+> sender-side payload shared-backed and allows the same payload to be sent again
+> while previous messages are still in-flight. Receivers may observe overwritten
+> latest bytes. Do not use this mode when every message must represent an
+> immutable snapshot.
+>
+> If the channel also uses the preallocated allocator, `send()` makes the sent
+> slot reusable for future `SharedMemory.withAllocator(..., { channel })`
+> scopes. Sender-side references kept after `send()` may therefore observe bytes
+> written by later allocations using the same slot.
+
+#### `channel.sendAndWait(data[, tag])` _Experimental_
+
+* `data` ArrayBuffer | ArrayBufferView - Shared-backed binary payload to queue.
+* `tag` number | null (optional) - Unsigned 32-bit integer tag used to route or
+  interpret the binary payload.
+
+Returns `Promise<void>` - Resolves after the main-process receiver has finished
+handling the message. If the receiver retains the message, the promise resolves
+after the retained lease is released.
+
+`sendAndWait` is for cases where the sender wants to reuse or overwrite the same
+shared-backed storage after the receiver is done. It uses a separate
+acknowledgement path. The fire-and-forget `send` method keeps the fastest
+notification path and does not wait for this acknowledgement. Unlike `send`,
+`sendAndWait` does not transfer ownership away from the sender.
+
+#### `channel.setMessageHandler(handler)` _Experimental_
+
+* `handler` Function\<Promise\<void\> | void\> | null
+  * `message` [SharedMemoryChannelMessage](structures/shared-memory-channel-message.md)
+
+Registers the channel message handler. Messages are delivered by directly
+calling this handler. If the handler returns a promise, `sendAndWait` resolves
+only after that promise settles. If the handler is synchronous, the channel does
+not use a promise dispatch path.
+
+If `views` is omitted from the receiver channel options, `message.view()` returns
+a `Uint8Array`. If `views` is supplied, messages must use a numeric tag listed
+in the map and `message.view()` returns the corresponding typed view. Untagged
+messages and messages with unregistered tags are reported to the channel error
+handler and are not delivered.
+
+```js
+const Payload = {
+  Bytes: 1,
+  Audio: 2,
+  Index: 3
+};
+
+const channel = Electron.SharedMemory.acceptChannel(pool, {
+  name: 'stream',
+  views: {
+    [Payload.Bytes]: Uint8Array,
+    [Payload.Audio]: Float32Array,
+    [Payload.Index]: Uint32Array
+  }
+});
+
+channel.setMessageHandler((message) => {
+  switch (message.tag) {
+    case Payload.Bytes: {
+      const bytes = message.view(); // Uint8Array
+      socket.send(message.data); // ArrayBuffer, no extra view needed.
+      break;
+    }
+    case Payload.Audio: {
+      const samples = message.view(); // Float32Array
+      processAudio(samples);
+      break;
+    }
+    case Payload.Index: {
+      const index = message.view(); // Uint32Array
+      updateIndex(index);
+      break;
+    }
+  }
+});
+```
+
+For TypeScript projects, numeric `enum` values work well with the same `views`
+map. A plain JavaScript-style object also works, but add `as const` if you want
+TypeScript to preserve numeric literal tags for `message.view()` narrowing.
+
+```ts
+enum Payload {
+  Bytes = 1,
+  Audio = 2,
+  Index = 3
+}
+
+const channel = Electron.SharedMemory.acceptChannel(pool, {
+  name: 'stream',
+  views: {
+    [Payload.Bytes]: Uint8Array,
+    [Payload.Audio]: Float32Array,
+    [Payload.Index]: Uint32Array
+  }
+});
+```
+
+#### `channel.setErrorHandler(handler)` _Experimental_
+
+* `handler` Function | null
+  * `error` Error
+
+Registers a handler for channel dispatch errors.
+
+#### `channel.setDropHandler(handler)` _Experimental_
+
+* `handler` Function | null
+  * `info` Object
+    * `count` number - Number of dropped messages.
+    * `reason` string - Drop reason.
+
+Registers a handler for channel drop notifications.
+
+#### `channel.close()` _Experimental_
+
+Closes this local channel endpoint and removes registered handlers.
